data.title: Phylum chordata
data.meta_description: Phylum chordata - Download as a PDF or view online for free
data.text:
1. Chordate Chordates are defined as organisms that possess a structure called a notochord, at least during some part of their development. The notochord is a rod that extends most of the length of the body when it is fully developed. Scientific classification Domain: Eukaryota Kingdm: Animalia Phylum: Chordata Chordates (phylum Chordata) are a group of animals that includes the vertebrates, together with several closely related invertebrates. They are united by having, at some time in their life cycle, a notochord, a hollow dorsal nerve cord, pharyngeal slits, an endostyle, and a post-anal tail. Some scientists argue that the true qualifier should be pharyngeal pouches rather than slits. Phylum Chordata (Sea Squirts and Vertebrate Animals) Class Amphibia (Amphibians)
